<div class="blog-faq"><h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

<div class="faq-item">
<h3>1. How do I know if a plastic surgeon is qualified?</h3>
<p>Check for board certification from recognized medical boards, membership in professional organizations like APSI or IAAPS, and verify their registration with the state medical council. You can also check hospital affiliations and training credentials.</p>
</div>

<div class="faq-item">
<h3>2. What is the difference between a plastic surgeon and a cosmetic surgeon?</h3>
<p>All plastic surgeons can perform cosmetic procedures, but not all cosmetic surgeons are trained plastic surgeons. Plastic surgeons complete a rigorous residency program that includes both reconstructive and cosmetic surgery training, while cosmetic surgeons may have shorter training focused only on aesthetic procedures.</p>
</div>

<div class="faq-item">
<h3>3. How many consultations should I have before choosing a surgeon?</h3>
<p>Most experts recommend consulting with at least two to three different surgeons before making a final decision. This allows you to compare approaches, comfort levels, and the quality of information provided during each consultation.</p>
</div>

<div class="faq-item">
<h3>4. Is it okay to choose a surgeon based on price?</h3>
<p>While cost is an important factor, it should never be the primary reason for choosing a surgeon. Extremely low prices can indicate compromised safety standards, inexperienced staff, or subpar facilities. Always prioritize qualifications and safety over cost.</p>
</div>

<div class="faq-item">
<h3>5. What red flags should I watch for during a consultation?</h3>
<p>Red flags include surgeons who pressure you into making a quick decision, refuse to show before-and-after photos, dismiss your concerns about risks, or recommend unnecessary procedures. A trustworthy surgeon will always prioritize your well-being and allow you time to decide.</p>
</div>

<div class="faq-item">
<h3>6. Should I get a second opinion before surgery?</h3>
<p>Absolutely. Getting a second opinion is a smart and responsible step, especially for major procedures. A confident surgeon will never discourage you from seeking another perspective and may even recommend it to ensure you feel fully informed.</p>
</div>

<div class="faq-item">
<h3>7. What should I bring to my first consultation?</h3>
<p>Bring a list of your questions, your medical history including current medications and allergies, photos of results you like (if applicable), and any previous medical records related to the area being treated. Being prepared helps you make the most of your consultation time.</p>
</div>

